        <ownerName>Eckhard</ownerName>
        <ownerEmail>e.pfluegel@gmail.com</ownerEmail>
    </head>
    <body>
        <outline text="Prerequisites.">
            <outline text="An understanding of advanced secret sharing techniques, including the Random Secret Sharing (RSS) protocol. "/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Aim.">
            <outline text="To illustrate the Random Secret Sharing (RSS) protocol. "/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Covered Learning Outcomes.">
            <outline text="CI7160 LO2, LO5"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Description.">
            <outline text="Setup.">
                <outline text="The class is divided into $$n$$ groups, recommended group number $$n$$ is between 3 and 4. Each group requires a unique index $$i$$."/>
                <outline text="Each group receives $$n$$ record cards of same colour."/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Instructions.">
                <outline text="You will simulate the RSS protocol. Revised the slide and familiarise yourself with its content. You will simulate the exchange of messages by physically passing on record cards."/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Activity.  " listStyle="arabic">
                <outline text="Write down your share on a separate piece of paper."/>
                <outline text="On each record card, note your group (player) ID at the top, the recipient (other players) ID at the bottom and the corresponding share value in the middle."/>
                <outline text="Send the various shares to their recipients, by passing on record cards."/>
                <outline text="Write down the final share, by adding up all the received shares and your own private share."/>
                <outline text="Are you now able to justify why everyone has a secret share of a random secret, which is not known to anyone at this stage?"/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Wrap-Up.">
                <outline text="Can you think of an application of this protocol?"/>
            </outline>
        </outline>
    </body>
</opml>
